===Verb===
{{en-verb|hears|hearing|heard}}

# {{intransitive}} To have the faculty of being able to [[perceive]] sounds, through the [[ear]]. {{defdate|from 10th c.}}
#:''I was deaf, and now I can '''hear'''.''
# {{transitive}} To [[perceive]] (a sound, or something producing a sound) with the [[ear]], to [[recognize]] (something) in an auditory way. {{defdate|from 10th c.}}
#:''I '''heard''' a sound from outside the window.''
# {{transitive}} To excercise this faculty [[intentionally]]; to [[listen]] to. {{defdate|from 10th c.}}
#*'''1526''', William Tyndale, trans. ''Bible'', John X:
#*:Agayne there was dissencion amonge the iewes for these sayinges, and many of them sayd: He hath the devyll, and is madde: why '''heare''' ye hym?
# {{transitive}} To listen favourably to; to [[grant]] (a request etc.). {{defdate|from 10th c.}}
#:''Eventually the king chose to '''hear''' her entreaties.''
# {{transitive}} To receive information about; to come to [[learn]] of. {{defdate|from 10th c.}}
#*'''1667''', John Milton, ''Paradise Lost'':
#*:Adam, soon as he '''heard''' / The fatal Trespass don by Eve, amaz'd, / Astonied stood and Blank [...].
# {{transitive}} To [[listen]] to (a person, case) in a court of law; to [[try]]. {{defdate|from 12th c.}}
#:''Your case will be '''heard''' at the end of the month.''

